WAYLAND — WHAT'S STILL DIFFERENT
--------------------------------

# fedora has been wayland-first for almost a decade — GNOME wayland
# default since F25 (2016), plasma wayland default since F36 (2022),
# F41 (2024) DROPPED the GNOME X11 session from the default install.
# you can put it back (`dnf install gnome-session-xsession`) but the
# direction is clear.
#
# the wayland transition is mostly complete for native apps and
# painfully incomplete for specific edge cases (automation, color
# pickers, some accessibility tooling). this section is what's still
# different.


# THE MENTAL MODEL — SECURITY OVER COMPATIBILITY

# X11 lets any app see / control any other app. that's the security
# bug, not a feature. wayland's design says: apps see only their own
# windows; system-wide capture / control requires explicit permission
# brokered by the compositor.
#
# every "thing that doesn't work the same on wayland" follows from
# that: screen recording (needs portal permission), global hotkeys
# (only the compositor can grab keys), clipboard managers (need to be
# part of the compositor), color pickers (need portal permission to
# read pixels), automation tools (need accessibility APIs or
# permission portals).
#
# the answer to "why doesn't X11 tool X work" is almost always: it
# would have to read or write things wayland doesn't let it. the
# answer is usually "use the portal-aware replacement".


# XWAYLAND — THE BACKWARDS COMPATIBILITY LAYER

# XWayland is an X11 server that runs as a wayland CLIENT. legacy X11
# apps connect to XWayland, which renders into a wayland surface. for
# most apps you don't notice — the app says "i'm an X app" and
# XWayland handles it.
#
# check what an app is using:
echo $XDG_SESSION_TYPE                         # wayland or x11
xlsclients -l                                  # X11 apps currently running

# you'll see things like Steam, older Electron apps, some JetBrains
# IDEs, OBS (in older configs), Wine apps — all via XWayland.
# performance is generally fine; HiDPI scaling is the most common
# pain point (XWayland apps may render blurry on fractional scales).

# the long tail: XWayland is here forever. it's not deprecated; both
# wayland and X11-via-XWayland will coexist indefinitely. don't worry
# about "porting" your X11 apps unless YOU maintain them.


# PIPEWIRE PORTALS — THE MAGIC THAT MAKES MODERN WAYLAND DESKTOPS WORK

# desktop portals (xdg-desktop-portal) are the system that brokers
# permission-needing operations: screen recording, file picker, screen
# sharing, GPU access, notifications. on wayland, screen capture
# specifically goes through PipeWire's video pipeline.
#
# verify the portal stack is running:
systemctl --user status xdg-desktop-portal
systemctl --user status xdg-desktop-portal-gnome     # GNOME backend
systemctl --user status xdg-desktop-portal-gtk       # GTK fallback
# (KDE users: substitute xdg-desktop-portal-kde)
#
# if these aren't running, browser screen sharing, OBS screen capture,
# flatpak file pickers, and GNOME's built-in screen recorder all fail
# silently or weirdly.


# SCREEN RECORDING

# native built-in (GNOME): Ctrl+Shift+Alt+R toggles recording. saved
# to ~/Videos/. limited but zero setup.
#
# OBS Studio — the canonical option. since OBS 28+ it speaks PipeWire
# portals natively. pick a "Screen Capture (PipeWire)" source; a
# portal dialog appears the first time asking which monitor / window.
sudo dnf install obs-studio
#
# gpu-screen-recorder — replay-buffer-focused option. low overhead.
# good for gaming highlights.
sudo dnf install gpu-screen-recorder
#
# wf-recorder — CLI for wlroots-based compositors (sway, hyprland).
# overkill for GNOME / Plasma which have built-in or OBS paths.


# SCREEN SHARING IN BROWSERS

# works on chrome / chromium / firefox via PipeWire portals. if it
# DOESN'T work, in order of probability:
#
# 1. xdg-desktop-portal services aren't running (see above)
# 2. browser is too old (chrome <90, firefox <94 don't support it)
