WHAT FEDORA WORKSTATION SHIPS BY DEFAULT
----------------------------------------

# fedora workstation curates its default install: enough to be a
# usable desktop OS, not so much that the ISO is bloated. assumption
# is you'll install your specific tools via dnf or flatpak.


# LANGUAGES & RUNTIMES (preinstalled)

# python 3        — `python` IS python 3. python 2 is gone.
# perl            — system tooling still depends on it
# bash            — default login shell
# ruby            — interpreter (some system tools need it)
# gawk, sed       — POSIX text-processing tools
# C / C++ compilers — NOT installed by default. come in via
#                   `@development-tools` or transitively from any
#                   `-devel` package install. verify:
rpm -q gcc gcc-c++ make
sudo dnf groupinstall "Development Tools"      # if missing


# SHELLS

# bash            — preinstalled (default)
# zsh, fish, etc. — NOT preinstalled. install on demand.


# CONTAINERS / VMs (preinstalled)

# podman, toolbox — preinstalled, blessed defaults (see CONTAINERS above)
# GNOME Boxes    — removed from the default install around F38. install
#                  via GNOME Software or `sudo dnf install gnome-boxes`.
# virt-manager   — not preinstalled. see VIRTUAL MACHINES section.


# GNOME APP SUITE (preinstalled)

# browser:        firefox
# core shell:     Files (Nautilus), Settings, Software, Tour, Help
# editor:         gnome-text-editor (replaced gedit in F42)
# terminal:       ptyxis (replaced gnome-terminal in F41)
# productivity:   Calculator, Calendar, Clocks, Weather, Maps
# system:         Disks, Disk Usage Analyzer (baobab), System Monitor,
#                 Logs, Software, Connections (RDP/VNC client)
# media:          Image Viewer (Loupe, replaced eog in F40),
#                 Videos (Totem), Snapshot (replaced Cheese for webcam)


# SYSTEM / NETWORK PLUMBING (preinstalled)

# init:           systemd
# networking:     NetworkManager, firewalld, OpenSSH client
# audio:          PipeWire + WirePlumber
# bluetooth:      BlueZ
# display:        GNOME Shell + Mutter, gdm (login manager)
# firmware:       fwupd (LVFS — see HARDWARE section)
# CLI:            nano, vim-minimal (`vi`, NOT full vim), less, curl, wget


# QUIETLY ABSENT — common installs

# most users add these within an hour of first boot:

# CLI productivity:
sudo dnf install ripgrep fd-find bat fzf jq htop tmux neovim

# dev toolchains beyond C / Python / Perl:
sudo dnf install golang rust cargo nodejs npm java-latest-openjdk \
    clang cmake ninja-build

# desktop apps not shipped by default:
#   - LibreOffice (removed from default ~F33; flatpak or dnf)
#   - Chrome (RPM Fusion or chrome's own repo)
#   - VS Code, JetBrains IDEs (Microsoft repo / flatpak / vendor)
#   - Slack, Zoom, Discord (flathub)
#   - Steam (RPM Fusion + multilib enabled via dnf groupinstall)

# multimedia codecs:
#   - H.264 / H.265 / AAC need RPM Fusion's ffmpeg swap (see REPOS).
#   - without it, video playback / hardware-accel encode is limited.

# proprietary nvidia driver:
#   - nouveau ships; akmod-nvidia is in RPM Fusion (see NVIDIA section).


# VERIFY WHAT'S ON YOUR BOX

# list every installed package
rpm -qa | wc -l                                # how many packages
rpm -qa | sort > ~/fedora-installed.txt

# what's USER-installed (not pulled in as a dep) — closest to a
# "what did I add" list:
sudo dnf repoquery --userinstalled --queryformat '%{name}\n' | sort

# what groups are installed
sudo dnf group list --installed

# is a specific package installed?
rpm -q gcc zsh gnome-boxes 2>&1


# WHY FEDORA WORKSTATION FEELS "MOSTLY THERE"

# the default install is deliberately curated for the system-level
# user — someone who'll bring their own toolchain, terminal, and
# editor preferences. that's why C devs, sysadmins, and SREs often
# find fedora "has most of what i need" without configuration:
# the things you'd want to install yourself anyway aren't preinstalled
# (because preferences differ), and the things everyone needs
# (firefox, file manager, terminal, image viewer, network tools)
# are there.
#
# this is also why GNOME developers themselves tend to use it as a
# daily driver — it's the reference platform for new GNOME releases,
# without the philosophical overhead of an immutable variant like
# Silverblue.


