FEDORA RELEASE HISTORY (2003 → present)
---------------------------------------

# 44 releases over 22+ years. the long arc tells a real story about
# how linux desktop evolved.


# PRE-FEDORA BASELINE (2003 and before)

# red hat linux was the dominant desktop linux distro from the late
# 90s through early 2000s. boxed sets at compusa, fry's, best buy:
# RHL 8 (2002), RHL 9 (March 2003). RHL 9 was the LAST.
#
# late 2003: red hat split. RHEL became the commercial subscription
# product (RHEL 3 had just launched in Oct 2003); fedora project became
# the community continuation.


# FEDORA CORE ERA (2003-2007) — RHL's community lineage

# Fedora Core 1 ("Yarrow")     — Nov 2003. kernel 2.4, GNOME 2.4,
#                                KDE 3.1. essentially RHL 9 rebranded
#                                with newer packages.
# Fedora Core 2 ("Tettnang")   — May 2004. linux 2.6 (huge jump).
#                                SELinux included (not enforcing).
#                                X.org replaced XFree86. infamous
#                                "ate my windows partition" GRUB bug.
# Fedora Core 3 ("Heidelberg") — Nov 2004. GCC 3.4, GNOME 2.8.
# Fedora Core 4 ("Stentz")     — Jun 2005. GCC 4.0, Eclipse + open Java
#                                by default. first PPC support.
# Fedora Core 5 ("Bordeaux")   — Mar 2006. Mono. graphical package
#                                tools (Pup / Pirut).
# Fedora Core 6 ("Zod")        — Oct 2006. compiz / AIGLX — the
#                                wobbly-windows era. OLPC partnership.

# the "Core" repo (red hat maintained) + "Extras" repo (community
# maintained) split caused dependency hell across the boundary.
# fedora 7 fixed it.


# FEDORA REBRAND (2007) — single repo, modern identity

# Fedora 7 ("Moonshine")  — May 2007. Core + Extras MERGED. just
#                           "Fedora" from here. custom spins, live USB.
# Fedora 8 ("Werewolf")   — Nov 2007. PulseAudio default (audio stack
#                           reset). IcedTea (open java).
# Fedora 9 ("Sulphur")    — May 2008. KDE 4.0 default (the controversial
#                           buggy release). ext4 preview. Firefox 3.
# Fedora 10 ("Cambridge") — Nov 2008. Plymouth boot animation replaced
#                           RHGB. Empathy IM.
# Fedora 11 ("Leonidas")  — Jun 2009. ext4 default. 20-second boot
#                           goal. devicekit / udisks.
# Fedora 12 ("Constantine") — Nov 2009. NetworkManager improvements.
# Fedora 13 ("Goddard")   — May 2010. nouveau 3D. btrfs preview.
# Fedora 14 ("Laughlin")  — Nov 2010. LAST GNOME 2 release (2.32).
#                           systemd available, not yet default.


# THE SYSTEMD / GNOME 3 TRANSITION (2011-2013) — most disruptive era

# Fedora 15 ("Lovelock")        — May 2011. GNOME 3.0 DEFAULT AND
#                                 systemd as DEFAULT INIT, same release.
#                                 brutal for users. linus famously
#                                 switched to XFCE here.
# Fedora 16 ("Verne")           — Nov 2011. GRUB 2 default.
# Fedora 17 ("Beefy Miracle")   — May 2012. /bin → /usr/bin merge
#                                 (UsrMove) — quietly massive change
#                                 for the filesystem hierarchy. the
#                                 codename became its own meme.
# Fedora 18 ("Spherical Cow")   — Jan 2013. delayed multiple times —
#                                 became the byword for "slipped
#                                 releases". new (much-hated) Anaconda
#                                 installer rewrite.
# Fedora 19 ("Schrödinger's Cat") — Jul 2013. OpenShift Origin. 3D
#                                 printer support.
# Fedora 20 ("Heisenbug")       — Dec 2013. 10TH ANNIVERSARY release.
#                                 systemd-journald replaced rsyslog
#                                 as default.


# FEDORA.NEXT ERA (2014-2018) — Editions split, DNF, modularity

# Fedora 21               — Dec 2014. CODENAMES DROPPED. split into
#                           Editions: Workstation, Server, Cloud.
#                           wayland preview. the big reorganization.
# Fedora 22               — May 2015. DNF replaced YUM. generational
#                           change in the package tool.
# Fedora 23               — Nov 2015. LibreOffice 5.
# Fedora 24               — Jun 2016. flatpak support introduced.
# Fedora 25               — Nov 2016. WAYLAND BY DEFAULT on GNOME —
#                           first major distro to do it. MP3 decoding
#                           enabled (patent finally expired). rust
#                           packaging.
# Fedora 26               — Jul 2017. EFI boot improvements.
# Fedora 27               — Nov 2017. Modular Server preview. Cloud
#                           edition retired (containers obsoleted it).
# Fedora 28               — May 2018. Modular Server stable.


# MODERN ERA (2018-2024) — atomic, btrfs, PipeWire

# Fedora 29  — Oct 2018. SILVERBLUE FIRST STABLE. the immutable
#              workstation arrives.
# Fedora 30  — May 2019. IoT edition official. ZRAM for low-memory.
# Fedora 31  — Oct 2019. PYTHON 2 EOL. cgroups v2 by default — this is
#              what broke docker on fedora and accelerated the move to
#              podman.
# Fedora 32  — Apr 2020. COVID-era release. EarlyOOM. python 2 fully
#              removed.
# Fedora 33  — Oct 2020. BTRFS AS DEFAULT FILESYSTEM. major change.
#              swap-on-zram by default. Kinoite stable (immutable KDE).
# Fedora 34  — Apr 2021. PIPEWIRE BY DEFAULT (replaced PulseAudio after
#              14 years). GNOME 40 — new horizontal workspace UI.
# Fedora 35  — Nov 2021. power-profiles-daemon by default (replacing
#              TLP for most). WirePlumber. Kinoite official Edition.
# Fedora 36  — May 2022. GNOME 42 — libadwaita era begins. Wayland
#              default for Plasma.
# Fedora 37  — Nov 2022. GNOME 43. Anaconda webui preview. Phosh spin
