# TERMINAL-FIRST SYSADMIN HABITS

# the terminal commands you'll use most often, mapped from gui muscle
# memory:
#
#   "what process is using my CPU"  → htop / btop / top
#   "what's listening on a port"    → ss -tlnp
#   "view system logs"              → journalctl -xb / journalctl -fu <service>
#   "service is broken"             → systemctl status <service>
#   "restart a service"             → sudo systemctl restart <service>
#   "check disk usage"              → df -h, du -sh, ncdu, dust
#   "find a file"                   → find / fd / locate
#   "search file contents"          → grep / ripgrep
#   "what's eating my RAM"          → free -h, htop's M sort
#   "kill an app"                   → killall <name>, xkill not on wayland
#
# you don't HAVE to memorize these. GNOME Settings + GNOME Software +
# System Monitor cover most needs. but every google answer for a real
# problem will be a terminal command. accept that and you'll move
# faster.


# DUAL-BOOT WITH WINDOWS — BRIEFLY

# common question, rarely the right answer in 2026. dual-boot was
# essential when linux gaming was bad and VMs were slow. now:
#   - VMs run windows well enough for most users (see VIRTUAL MACHINES)
#   - proton runs most games well enough (see GAMING stub)
#   - office and adobe have web versions
#
# if you DO dual-boot:
#   - install windows FIRST, fedora second. windows' bootloader
#     overwrites fedora's; fedora's grub respects windows.
#   - leave 50+ GB unallocated when installing windows so fedora has
#     room.
#   - fedora's anaconda installer will auto-detect windows and add
#     it to grub.
#   - keep separate filesystems. don't try to share home dirs across
#     OSes — NTFS works for data sharing if you must.


# THINGS THAT GENUINELY WORK BETTER ON LINUX

# real wins worth recognizing so you know you've gained something:
#
#   - PACKAGE MANAGEMENT. one command updates everything; no
#     individual app self-updaters; no "click here to update" popups.
#   - TERMINAL. a real shell with a real package ecosystem.
#     wsl tried to bring this to windows; it's still less integrated
#     than the native thing.
#   - NO ADS IN THE OS. no "did you know you can try edge" nags,
#     no recommendations on the start menu, no game ads in the
#     control panel.
#   - UPDATES THAT DON'T HIJACK YOUR DAY. fedora upgrades run when
#     you tell them to. no "updating, do not turn off your PC"
#     for 45 minutes.
#   - DEV ENVIRONMENT. installing a development stack on linux is
#     measured in minutes, not hours. see SHELL AND DEV-ENVIRONMENT.
#   - CUSTOMIZATION. GNOME extensions, KDE customization, window
#     manager tiling, any keyboard layout you want.
#   - REMOTE ADMINISTRATION. ssh into anything; full system access
#     from a phone.
#   - WORKSPACES THAT ACTUALLY WORK. macos and windows both have
#     workspaces but they're awkward; GNOME's horizontal workspace
#     paradigm is genuinely good once you adapt.


# THINGS THAT ARE WORSE — AND HOW TO COPE

# 1. ADOBE CREATIVE CLOUD. no native support. cope:
#    - photopea.com for raster editing (web)
#    - GIMP for daily raster (free)
#    - Darktable for Lightroom-style RAW workflow
#    - Inkscape for Illustrator-style vector work
#    - DaVinci Resolve free for Premiere-style video editing
#    - Krita for digital art
#    - if you MUST run Photoshop: windows VM with GPU passthrough,
#      see VIRTUAL MACHINES.
#
# 2. SPECIFIC GAMES. proton handles ~80% of windows games. the 20%
#    that don't work are usually competitive multiplayer with kernel
#    anti-cheat. check protondb.com before assuming.
#
# 3. SOME VENDOR-SPECIFIC TOOLS. if your bank requires a specific
#    java applet, or your university uses a tool that's windows-only,
#    keep a windows VM for those occasions.
#
# 4. ICLOUD ECOSYSTEM (mac users). there's no full replacement.
#    Signal + Matrix + KDE Connect get you close. accept the loss.
#
# 5. SOME COLOR-MANAGED WORKFLOWS. photography / print workflow
#    color management on linux works but is more manual than macos.
#    Darktable + colord + display calibration probes (DisplayCAL) get
#    you there; expect 1-2 evenings of setup.
#
# 6. SLEEP/RESUME ON SOME HARDWARE. windows has tighter integration
#    with vendor firmware for s0ix (modern standby). on some laptops
#    linux sleep is less battery-efficient. see POWER MANAGEMENT;
#    `fwupdmgr update` to firmware-update first.


# MIGRATING YOUR ACTUAL FILES

# windows backup → fedora:
#   - external drive with copied folders → mount + rsync
#   - File History backups → restore on a windows machine first,
#     then copy the data over
#   - cloud-based (OneDrive web, Dropbox, etc.) → log in on fedora
#     and re-sync
#   - direct windows → linux copy via NTFS: install `ntfs-3g`
#     (preinstalled), mount the partition, copy out

# macos backup → fedora:
#   - Time Machine: backups are HFS+ or APFS. restore on a mac first,
#     copy to an external drive in exfat or NTFS, then copy to linux.
#     OR: use `apfs-fuse` (third-party, less reliable) to read APFS
#     directly on linux.
#   - cloud (iCloud Drive web export, Dropbox, etc.) → log in on
#     fedora.
#   - direct mac → linux: format an external drive as exFAT, copy
#     files via Finder, plug into linux.


# FIRST-WEEK SANITY CHECKS

# things to verify work on YOUR hardware before assuming the migration
# is solid:
#
#   - wifi connects + survives suspend
#   - bluetooth pairs + audio routes correctly (see AUDIO)
#   - suspend / resume works (see POWER MANAGEMENT)
#   - brightness keys work + persist across reboots
#   - microphone works in zoom or meet
#   - external monitor detected; if multi-monitor, layout is correct
#   - touchpad gestures work (3-finger swipe for workspaces)
#   - HiDPI scales sanely (200% if hi-res, fractional otherwise)
#   - fwupd has no critical pending updates: `fwupdmgr get-updates`
#   - print to your usual printer (see PRINTING / SCANNING stub)
#   - your password manager works
#   - your two-factor auth (yubikey, etc) works


# WHEN TO PERSIST AND WHEN TO BAIL

# most migration issues resolve in week one. give it 3-4 weeks of
# real work before judging. expect the first week to feel slower —
# you're re-learning muscle memory. by week 4 you should be at the
# productivity of your previous OS, with strict improvements in
# package management, terminal, customization, and absence of ads.
#
# the migrations that DON'T stick are usually:
#   - users dependent on a specific adobe / autodesk / lightroom
#     workflow they're unwilling to substitute
#   - users dependent on competitive multiplayer gaming with kernel
#     anti-cheat
#   - users in highly-vendor-locked corporate environments
#
# none of these are wrong reasons to bail. linux isn't a religion.
# but most users find the migration sticks once the initial friction
# fades.


WHY UBUNTU USERS MIGRATE TO FEDORA
----------------------------------

# a recurring driver of fedora adoption is friction with canonical's
# commercial layer on ubuntu. some of this is "proprietary" in the
# strict sense (closed-source); some is "intrusive" (ads + nags inside
# an open distro). the honest taxonomy of what people object to:


# THE BIG ONES (most-cited in migration posts)

# 1. SNAP STORE BACKEND IS PROPRIETARY. snap as a packaging format is
#    open source, but snapcraft.io — the ONLY place snaps come from —
#    is a closed canonical-run service. you can't host your own. compare
#    with flatpak: flathub is one of many possible remotes. single-
#    vendor lock-in inside an "open" distro is the core objection.
#
# 2. `apt install firefox` SILENTLY INSTALLS THE SNAP. on ubuntu,
#    certain packages (firefox, chromium, thunderbird in some versions)
#    are no longer real .debs — apt redirects to snap under the hood.
#    no prompt, no opt-out at the apt level. this broke the "deb on
#    ubuntu" mental model and lit a fire under the migration crowd.
#
# 3. MANDATORY SNAP AUTO-UPDATES. snapd updates installed snaps on its
#    own schedule. delay (`snap refresh --hold`) but you can't disable
#    cleanly. for a desktop user editing a file when firefox restarts
#    itself, this is a genuine grievance.


# THE INTRUSIVE ADVERTISING LAYER

# 4. APT NEWS. canonical promotional messages injected into `apt update`
#    output, mostly recommending ubuntu pro. disable:
#         sudo pro config set apt_news=false
#    (see [[ubuntu]] for the one-liner.)
#
# 5. MOTD ADVERTISING. ssh or local TTY login on ubuntu server prints
#    canonical promotional text — pro encouragement, blog links,
#    surveys. lives in /etc/update-motd.d/; chmod -x the offenders.
#
# 6. `pro security-status` NAGS. apt output and motd periodically
#    report on "expired security updates" ubuntu pro would cover.
#    technically informational; reads like a paywall warning.


# UBUNTU PRO ITSELF

# 7. UBUNTU PRO IS A PAID CANONICAL SUBSCRIPTION (free for personal
#    use up to 5 machines; paid otherwise). it provides "esm-apps"
#    and "esm-infra" — extended security maintenance for packages
#    ubuntu's free tier doesn't get past their support window. the
#    implication: parts of the package set get patched only for
#    paying customers. the most contentious change for shops running
#    ubuntu LTS in production.
#
# 8. EVEN WITHOUT SUBSCRIBING, ubuntu-advantage-tools is INSTALLED
#    and the `pro` CLI phones home to check entitlements. removable
#    but on by default.


# OTHER COMMERCIALLY-TIED BITS

# 9.  LIVEPATCH (kernel live patching) requires ubuntu pro. marketed
#     heavily.
# 10. LANDSCAPE — canonical's commercial fleet-management product.
#     mentioned in motd / pro outputs even if you don't use it.
# 11. SNAPD PHONE-HOME. snapd contacts canonical periodically for
#     refresh checks. standard PM behavior, but combined with the
#     lock-in story it gets called out.


# HISTORICAL BAGGAGE (mostly gone but stains the reputation)

# 12. AMAZON SEARCH LENS (2012-2016). unity dash sent your search
#     terms to amazon for affiliate revenue. removed by 16.04. the
#     "original sin" that taught users to scrutinize canonical
#     product decisions.
# 13. MIR (canonical's NIH display server vs wayland), UNITY (insular
#     DE), UPSTART (init before systemd). examples of canonical
#     fragmenting linux through NIH. all irrelevant today, but
#     contribute to the long-tail trust deficit.


# WHAT FEDORA EXPLICITLY DOESN'T DO

# - no paid subscription tier (RHEL is the paid product, a separate
#   distro entirely)
# - no proprietary store backend (RPM Fusion and COPR are community-run;
#   flathub is the default flatpak remote, you can add others)
# - no advertising in dnf output or motd
# - no `pro`-equivalent nag tool
# - no silent `dnf install` redirects to a different package format


# THE FAIR CAVEAT

# fedora is sponsored by red hat (now IBM), and red hat has made its
# own controversial decisions in recent years (RHEL source code access
# changes in 2023). the meaningful difference: those decisions
# affect the COMMERCIAL product, not the upstream community distro.
# fedora the experience hasn't been monetized.
#
# this isn't a "canonical bad, red hat good" story. canonical has a
# business model; companies need revenue. the question is whether the
# line where commercial intent intrudes on user experience is
# acceptable. for many ex-ubuntu users, the line has been crossed.


WHY PEOPLE TRY ARCH / NIX AND COME BACK
---------------------------------------

# one of the most common patterns in linux desktop life: a fedora user
# gets curious about a trending distro, takes the detour, and returns
# 6-12 months later. the shapes are different for arch and nix; the
# underlying lesson is the same.


# WHY PEOPLE LEAVE ARCH AFTER TRYING IT

# 1. MAINTENANCE BECOMES THE HOBBY. reading archlinux.org/news before
#    every -Syu, merging .pacnew files, the "never pacman -Sy without
#    -u" landmine, keyring expiry after a vacation. small individually;
#    cumulatively a part-time job. the realization "i could be writing
#    code instead" is the actual exit point.
#
# 2. AUR BREAKAGE AT THE WRONG MOMENT. a dep you rely on builds against
#    a library that just bumped — now you're patching a PKGBUILD on a
#    tuesday afternoon when you needed to ship.
#
# 3. THE NOVELTY WEARS OFF. installing arch is a rite of passage you
#    only need to pass once. the second time it's just chores. the
#    pride doesn't survive iteration.
#
# 4. BLEEDING-EDGE BITES HARDWARE. a kernel bump regresses nvidia,
#    suspend/resume on your laptop, an audio quirk. the fix arrives
#    in a week — you needed the laptop yesterday.
#
# 5. THE DOTFILE-DRIFT PROBLEM. every arch install ends up slightly
#    different from your last one. minimalism sells the install; it
#    doesn't sell the maintenance.


# WHY PEOPLE LEAVE NIXOS AFTER TRYING IT

# 1. THE NIX LANGUAGE IS HARD. a custom DSL, lazy-evaluated, notoriously
#    poor error messages, weird scoping. you wanted a config file; you
#    got a programming language. months in, you're an amateur nix
#    programmer instead of using your computer.
#
# 2. DOCUMENTATION IS FRAGMENTED AND AGES FAST. wiki, manual,
#    nixos-options, search.nixos.org, discourse, blog posts — no
#    canonical source, and the language moves faster than the docs.
#    every problem requires triangulating three sources, two outdated.
#
# 3. IMPERATIVE ESCAPE HATCHES EVERYWHERE. when something doesn't fit
#    nix's model — proprietary binaries, vendor SDKs, anything compiled
#    for "normal" linux — you end up in steam-run, nix-ld, patchelf, or
#    FHS environments. the clean abstraction leaks constantly.
#
# 4. LONG, SLOW REBUILDS. `nixos-rebuild switch` on a meaningful config
#    takes minutes; on flake setups often more. compare with `dnf
#    install foo` finishing in seconds.
#
# 5. REPRODUCIBILITY PROMISE VS PRACTICE. flakes vs channels, impure
#    evaluation, IFD, pinning strategies — five different ways to do
#    everything and the community disagrees on which is canonical. the
#    "just works" property hides a thicket of decisions.
#
# 6. DISK BALLOONS. every config change is a new generation; without
#    aggressive garbage collection, /nix/store grows to hundreds of GB.
#
# 7. COMMUNITY FROUGHT. governance disputes, moderation controversies,
#    the nix/nixos foundation drama (2024). the social environment
#    hasn't been as calm as the technical concept.


# WHAT PULLS PEOPLE BACK

# the same thing that kept linus there — the distro becomes invisible.
# specifically:
#
#   - SENSIBLE DEFAULTS YOU DON'T HAVE TO ARGUE WITH. GNOME, systemd,
#     NetworkManager, firewalld. you CAN change them but don't HAVE to
#     think about them.
#   - POLISHED TOOLING. anaconda, GNOME settings, cockpit, GNOME
#     software. not minimal but works without config.
#   - PREDICTABLE CADENCE. 6-month releases on a calendar vs a continuous
#     trickle (arch) vs every-config-change rebuild (nix).
#   - YOU CAN IMPERATIVELY CHANGE THINGS. install nvidia? `sudo dnf
#     install akmod-nvidia`. not "edit configuration.nix, rebuild,
#     reboot, hope". most computer tasks ARE imperative; matching that
#     is a feature.
#   - CALM COMMUNITY. fedora has very little drama. governance is
#     boring. nobody is shouting on reddit about a forced migration.
#   - HARDWARE WITHOUT EFFORT. fwupd, kernel curation, akmod-nvidia,
#     libfprint — all the things you'd otherwise spend weekends on.
#   - CONTAINERS AS THE ESCAPE HATCH. when you want a different distro
#     for a task, toolbox / distrobox give you it without committing
#     the host. the features nix sells you (isolated environments)
#     are available cheaply (see CONTAINERS section).
#   - TRANSFERABLE SKILLS. fedora knowledge transfers to RHEL, which
#     transfers to half the corporate linux world. nixos skills
#     transfer to nixos.


# THE DEEPER PATTERN

# arch and nix sell you the SYSTEM as the interesting object. fedora
# sells the system as the SUBSTRATE — its job is to disappear so you
# can focus on what runs on top.
#
# both arch and nix promise that the visibility is worth it: that
# hand-tuning or precisely declaring your system will pay dividends.
# for a small minority of users, it genuinely does. for most, it turns
# out the system being INVISIBLE is the actual desirable property. you
# don't realize that's what you wanted until you've tried the
# alternative and felt the weight of system-as-hobby.
#
# coming back to fedora isn't admitting defeat. it's discovering what
# you actually need a computer FOR — which is usually not "be a nix
# programmer" or "be an arch maintainer". it's whatever you cared
# about before you got pulled into distro-tinkering.
#
# this is the same realization that drove the [[arch-distros]]
# exploration and the [[fedora-to-endeavouros]] migration plan
# captured elsewhere in this repo. not unique — a well-worn path.


WHY FEDORA — A NOTE ON THE LINUS PERSPECTIVE
--------------------------------------------

# Linus Torvalds has run fedora as his daily driver for ~20 years and
# counting. across interviews, mailing-list posts, and DebConf-style
# talks he's been consistent about why. paraphrased:
#
# 1. HE WANTS THE DISTRO TO BE INVISIBLE.
#    "i'm not interested in fighting my distro; i want to fight my code."
#    a kernel maintainer can't afford for the desktop OS to be a project
#    in itself. fedora installs, hardware works, he writes kernel code.
#
# 2. HARDWARE SUPPORT WAS THE ORIGINAL DRAW. early on (mid-2000s) he was
#    on PowerPC G5 macs and fedora had the best PPC support among the
#    big distros. as he moved to x86 and later experimented with ARM
#    development boxes, fedora kept up. it's been the path of least
#    friction on every machine he's used.
#
# 3. REASONABLY CURRENT WITHOUT BEING BLEEDING-EDGE. kernel devs need
#    recent toolchains (gcc, glibc, binutils, perf) — fedora ships them
#    within weeks of upstream. but every package update is a tiny risk
#    surface, and the 6-month cadence gives him fewer disruptions than
#    a true rolling distro would. he's been explicit that he's tried
#    rolling and prefers point releases.
#
# 4. HE DOESN'T CARE ABOUT DISTRO RELIGION. he's said many times he's
#    not loyal to fedora as an ideology. he just hasn't found a reason
#    to switch. picking a distro is logistics, not identity.
#
# 5. SENSIBLE DEFAULTS. out of the box, fedora doesn't make him
#    configure things to reach a working desktop. the kernel choice,
#    toolchain, default GNOME — they're all already there.
#
# 6. INERTIA, HONESTLY. once you're set up productively, switching has
#    a cost. that's a perfectly valid reason and he says so.

# FUN FOOTNOTE: in 2011 when GNOME 3 dropped, Linus very publicly tore
# into it ("an unholy mess") and switched to XFCE for a while. he
# stayed on FEDORA the whole time, just changed DE. he's since rotated
# through several DEs and is back to using mainstream ones. the point:
# the distro choice survived even a DE he hated.

# THE FRAME WORTH STEALING:
# Linus is explicit that his distro choice is NOT a recommendation. any
# reasonable distro works. but the frame is useful: if your distro is
# invisible enough that you stop thinking about it, you've picked
# correctly. the question isn't "which distro is best" — it's "which
# one lets me forget i picked one."
#
# this is exactly the test that turned [[arch-distros]] and the
# [[fedora-to-endeavouros]] migration into a "stay on fedora" decision:
# rolling-release maintenance demands attention; fedora doesn't.


